Your quote:
--
&gt;I have no difficulties with the current default behavior. 
--
You have no difficulties with the current default behavior because you are
JUnit-experienced, are very clever and use JUnit a lot.

Others are not so lucky. I consider myself to be among the
not-so-lucky-group.

I continue to submit that changing this aspect of JUnit would be the right
thing to do.

	whatever

&gt; -----Original Message-----
&gt; From:	Joi Ellis [SMTP:joi@...]
&gt; Sent:	Tuesday, March 27, 2001 1:16 PM
&gt; To:	junit@yahoogroups.com
&gt; Subject:	Re: [junit] -noloader (was: cannot run testing with UI
&gt; TestRunner?)
&gt; 
&gt; On Tue, 27 Mar 2001, Chas Schley wrote:
&gt; 
&gt; &gt; What to do?  I say keep the feature (and all of its blessings), but
&gt; &gt; don&#39;t make it the default behavior.  I.e., don&#39;t put people in a
&gt; position
&gt; &gt; that they have to find out the hard way.  Let&#39;s cause JUnit 3.6 to have
&gt; a
&gt; &gt; &quot;-loader&quot; flag that would enable the ReloadingTestSuiteLoader.  When
&gt; that
&gt; &gt; flag isn&#39;t given, then JUnit will use Java&#39;s default class loader.
&gt; &gt; Then, JUnit&#39;s default class loading behavior will be Java&#39;s default
&gt; &gt; class loading behavior.  It&#39;s more intuitive that way anyway.
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; Discussion is warmly invited, as long as it&#39;s professional.  Flames to
&gt; NLA0:
&gt; 
&gt; I learned about the class loader issue a year ago.  The instant I have
&gt; a wierd problem with a test, I run it twice, once under swingui and again
&gt; with textui.
&gt; 
&gt; If it runs under textui but not swingui, my next step is to add -noloading
&gt; to swingui.  That has always solved the problem, and -noloading goes 
&gt; right into the project&#39;s launcher from that point onward.
&gt; 
&gt; This loading/noloading trick is necessary for JNI debugging as well,
&gt; because with JNI the JVM will load a library at most once, no matter
&gt; what classloader is involved.
&gt; 
&gt; I have no difficulties with the current default behavior.  The GUI
&gt; interfaces, which you like to leave up and running, must obviously
&gt; be using the custom classloader, because otherwise you&#39;re just restesting
&gt; old classes already in the JVM.  TextUI doesn&#39;t stay running and doesn&#39;t
&gt; take long to load, so it doesn&#39;t use the custom classloader.
&gt; 
&gt; Beyond beating this topic into the ground in the documentation, I don&#39;t
&gt; see the need to change anything in JUnit.
&gt; 
&gt; -- 
&gt; Joi Ellis                    Software Engineer
&gt; Aravox Technologies          joi@..., gyles19@...
&gt; 
&gt; No matter what we think of Linux versus FreeBSD, etc., the one thing I
&gt; really like about Linux is that it has Microsoft worried.  Anything
&gt; that kicks a monopoly in the pants has got to be good for something.
&gt;            - Chris Johnson
